, Champagne-Ardenne, France","Of, Montmirail, Marne, France":"Montmirail, Marne, Champagne-Ardenne, France","Montmirail, Marne, Grand Est, France":"Montmirail, Marne, Grand Est, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"DE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"LA","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Cuong, Anh, Thanh, Ha, Hoang, Tuan, Chau, Hao, Hien, Hoa, Hue, Nam, Phong, Sinh, Tuong, Min, Tam, Tanh, Thai, Tham, Tinh, Yeong.  Chinese Hong, Hang, Sang, Tong, Chan, Chi, Hwa Ja, Hyung, Kam, Ki Bong, Kin, Man.","Vietnamese: from the Chinese surname 羅, see   Luo   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Lã</b>): from the Chinese surname 呂, see   Lu   6 and 3 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Luo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Jian, Yi, Ping, Yong, Zhen, Feng, Hong, Ming, Jin, Bin, Chen, Hai, Lan, Min, Huan, Hung, Shen, Tian.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 羅, meaning ‘net for catching birds’ or ‘to collect’ in Chinese: (i) from Luo (羅), the name of an ancient state (located in present-day Hubei province). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the early Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), people from the state migrated southwards and adopted Luo (羅) as their surname. (ii) from the Po Duo Luo (破多羅) and Chi Luo (叱羅) families from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China, who changed their original surnames to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) from the personal name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅), leader of an ancient Turkic tribe who are believed to have migrated to China during the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ). His descendants inherited his name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅) as their surname and shortened it to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iv) from the name of one of the seven families from the Bandun Man, an ethnic group residing in ancient southwestern China (located mainly in present-day Sichuan province)."]}]},{"name":"FERTE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German:","variant of   Fett   or   Fath  .","from a short form of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with <i>frid</i> ‘peace’ like   Friedrich   for example."],"variants":[{"name":"Fetty","meanings":["Possibly an Americanized form of German   Fette   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Fettig","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Mathias, Benno, Helmut, Kurt, Wendelin.","German:","in the north, a patronymic from   Fette  ."]},{"name":"Fett","meanings":["North German: nickname for a fat man, from Middle Low German <i>vett</i> ‘fat’.","English: nickname from Middle English <i>fet(te)</i>, <i>fait</i> ‘suitable, becoming, comely’ (Old French <i>fait</i>). Compare   Fettes  .","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farms named with Old Norse <i>fit</i> ‘meadow’."]}]},{"name":"GAUCHER","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Armand, Francoise, Jacques, Laurette, Lucien, Philippe.","French:","from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Walhari</i>, composed of the elements <i>walh</i> ‘stranger’ and <i>hari</i> ‘army’."],"variants":[{"name":"Coetzee","meanings":["Afrikaans: probably an altered form of Dutch <b>Goetzee</b>, which is of French Huguenot origin, probably from   Gaucher  . Alternatively, <i>Coetzee</i> may be an altered form of Dutch <b>Kuzee</b>, a habitational name recorded in the 16th century as <i>Cudsee</i> and <i>Cutsee</i>, from a toponym located in Zeeland, which may be interpreted as <i>Cut's-see</i> ‘watercourse of Cudo’.","History: Dirk Coetzee, born in Kampen in the Netherlands around 1655, died in Cape Town in 1725."]}]},{"name":"Hélie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an early medieval personal name, a derivative of <i>heilagr</i> ‘prosperous’. The popularity of the name greatly increased with the subsequent change in meaning of the vocabulary word to ‘blessed, holy’."],"variants":[{"name":"Helje","meanings":["From an early medieval personal name, a derivative of <i>heilagr</i> ‘prosperous’. The popularity of the name greatly increased with the subsequent change in meaning of the vocabulary word to ‘blessed, holy’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hélie DE LA FERTE GAUCHER was born in 1100, in Montmirail, Marne, Champagne-Ardenne, France, his father, Gaucher II DE MONTMIRAIL, was 26 and his mother, Élisabeth DE CHATILLON, was 17. He had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Adelaïde DE PLEURS. He died before 1145."},"et":{"1100–before 1145":"1100–enne 1145","1100–1145":"1100–1145","1105–1155":"1105–1155","1110–1171":"1110–1171","1126–1180":"1126–1180","1133–1189":"1133–1189","–1232":"–1232","–Male":"Surnud","1075–1123":"1075–1123","1084–1145":"1084–1145","environ 1123":"umbes 1123","before 1145":"enne 1145","1110":"1110","Abt 1126":"umbes 1126","1075":"1075","1084":"1084","1171":"1171","1180":"1180","1105":"1105","1126":"1126","1123":"1123","1189":"1189","1145":"1145","1100":"1100","1232":"1232","1133":"1133","1155":"1155","about 1133":"umbes 1133","Montmirail, Sarthe, Pays-de-la-Loire, Française":"Mo